1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO DEREGULATE NATURAL HAIR CARE; TO LICENSE HAIR DESIGNERS;
3 TO REDUCE THE AMOUNT OF TRAINING REQUIRED FOR COSMETOLOGISTS;
4 AND TO ELIMINATE LICENSURE AS AN APPRENTICE, AS RECOMMENDED BY
5 THE JOINT LEGISLATIVE ADMINISTRATIVE PROCEDURE OVERSIGHT
6 COMMITTEE; AND TO ALLOW MOBILE COSMETIC ART SHOPS.
7 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
8 SECTION 1. Chapter 88B of the General Statutes, as amended by S.L. 2025-20,
9 reads as rewritten:
10 "Chapter 88B.
11 "Cosmetic Art.
12 "§ 88B-1. Short title.
13 This chapter shall be known and may be cited as the North Carolina Cosmetic Art Act.
14 "§ 88B-2. Definitions.
15 The following definitions apply in this Chapter:
16 (1) Apprentice. – A person who is not a manager or operator and who is engaged
17 in learning the practice of cosmetic art under the direction and supervision of
18 a cosmetologist.
19 (2) Board. – The North Carolina Board of Cosmetic Art Examiners.
20 (3) Booth. – A workstation located within a licensed cosmetic art shop or mobile
21 cosmetic art shop that is operated primarily by one individual in performing
22 cosmetic art services for consumers.
23 (4) Booth renter. – A person who rents a booth in a cosmetic art shop.shop or
24 mobile cosmetic art shop.
25 (5) Cosmetic art. – All or any part or combination of cosmetology, hair design,
26 esthetics, natural hair care, or manicuring, including the systematic
27 manipulation with the hands or mechanical apparatus of the scalp, face, neck,
28 shoulders, hands, and feet. Practices included within this subdivision shall not
29 include the practice of massage or bodywork therapy as set forth in Article 36
30 of Chapter 90 of the General Statutes.
31 (6) Cosmetic art school. – Any building or part thereof where cosmetic art is
32 taught.
33 (7) Cosmetic art shop. – Any building or part thereof where cosmetic art is
34 practiced for pay or reward, whether direct or indirect.
35 (8) Cosmetologist. – Any individual who is licensed to practice all parts of
36 cosmetic art.
*S808-v-2*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (8a) Cosmetology. – The act of arranging, dressing, curling, waving, cleansing,
2 cutting, singeing, bleaching, coloring, or similar work upon the hair of a
3 person by any means, including the use of hands, mechanical or electrical
4 apparatus, or appliances or by use of cosmetic or chemical preparations or
5 antiseptics.
6 (9) Cosmetology teacher. – An individual licensed by the Board to teach all parts
7 of cosmetic art.
8 (10) Esthetician. – An individual licensed by the Board to practice only that part of
9 cosmetic art that constitutes skin care.
10 (11) Esthetician teacher. – An individual licensed by the Board to teach only that
11 part of cosmetic art that constitutes skin care.
12 (11a) Esthetics. – Refers to any of the following practices: giving facials; applying
13 makeup; performing skin care; removing superfluous hair from the body of a
14 person by use of creams, tweezers, or waxing; applying eyelashes to a person,
15 including the application of eyelash extensions, brow or lash color;
16 beautifying the face, neck, arms, or upper part of the human body by use of
17 cosmetic preparations, antiseptics, tonics, lotions, or creams; surface
18 manipulation in relation to skin care; or cleaning or stimulating the face, neck,
19 ears, arms, hands, bust, torso, legs, or feet of a person by means of hands,
20 devices, apparatus, or appliances along with the use of cosmetic preparations,
21 antiseptics, tonics, lotions, or creams.
22 (11b) Hair design. – The act of (i) arranging, dressing, curling, waving, cleansing,
23 cutting, singeing, bleaching, coloring, or similar work upon the hair of a
24 person by any means, including the use of hands, mechanical or electrical
25 apparatus, or appliances or by use of cosmetic or chemical preparations or
26 antiseptics; or (ii) removing superfluous hair from the face of a person by use
27 of waxing.
28 (11c) Hair design teacher. – An individual licensed by the Board to teach hair
29 design.
30 (11d) Hair designer. – An individual licensed by the Board to practice only that part
31 of cosmetic art that constitutes hair design.
32 (11e) Licensee. – An individual who holds one or more licenses or certifications
33 issued by the Board.
34 (12) Manicuring. – The care and treatment of the fingernails, toenails, cuticles on
35 fingernails and toenails, and the hands and feet, including the decoration of
36 the fingernails and the application of nail extensions and artificial nails. The
37 term "manicuring" shall not include the treatment of pathologic conditions.
38 (13) Manicurist. – An individual licensed by the Board to practice only that part of
39 cosmetic art that constitutes manicuring.
40 (14) Manicurist teacher. – An individual licensed by the Board to teach
41 manicuring.
42 (14a) Mobile cosmetic art shop. – A motor home as defined in Article 1 of Chapter
43 20 of the General Statutes that is used for the practice of cosmetic art for pay
44 or reward, whether direct or indirect.
45 (14b) Natural hair care. – A service that results in tension on hair strands or roots by
46 twisting, wrapping, extending, or locking hair by hand or mechanical device.
47 For purposes of this definition, the phrase "natural hair care" shall include the
48 use of artificial or natural hair.
49 (14b)(14c) Natural hair care specialist. – An individual licensed certified by the Board
50 to practice only that part of cosmetic art that constitutes natural hair care.
