9 "§ 88B-21. Renewals; expired licenses; inactive status.
10 (a) Each license to operate a cosmetic art shop or mobile cosmetic art shop shall be
11 renewed on or before the first day of February of each year. As provided in G.S. 88B-20, a late
12 fee shall be charged for licenses renewed after February 1. Any license not renewed by March 1
13 of each year shall expire. A cosmetic art shop or mobile cosmetic art shop whose license has
14 been expired for one year or less shall have the license reinstated immediately upon payment of
15 the reinstatement fee, the late fee, and all unpaid license fees. The licensee shall submit to the
16 Board, as a part of the renewal process, a list of all licensed cosmetologists who practice cosmetic
17 art in the shop and shall identify each as an employee or a booth renter.
18 (b) Cosmetologist licenses shall be renewed on or before October 1 every three years
19 beginning October 1, 1998. A late fee shall be charged for renewals after that date. Any license
20 not renewed shall expire on October 1 of the year that renewal is required. The Board may
21 develop and implement a plan for staggered license renewal and may prorate license fees to
22 implement such a plan.
23 (c) Apprentice, Hair designer, esthetician, natural hair care specialist, and manicurist
24 licenses or certifications shall be renewed annually on or before October 1 of each year. A late
25 fee shall be charged for the renewal of licenses or certifications after that date. Any license or
26 certification not renewed shall expire on October 1 of that year.
27 (d) Teacher licenses shall be renewed every two years on or before October 1. A late fee
28 shall be charged for the renewal of licenses after that date. Any license not renewed shall expire
29 on October 1 of that year.
30 (e) Prior to renewal of a certification or license, a teacher, cosmetologist, hair designer,
31 esthetician, natural hair care specialist, or manicurist shall annually complete eight four hours of
32 Board-approved continuing education for each year of the licensing cycle. A cosmetologist may
33 complete up to 24 hours 12 hours of required continuing education at any time within the
34 cosmetologist's three-year licensing cycle. Licensees shall submit written documentation to the
35 Board showing that they have satisfied the requirements of this subsection. A licensee who is in
36 active practice as a cosmetologist, hair designer, esthetician, natural hair care specialist, or
37 manicurist, has practiced for at least 10 consecutive years in that profession, and is 60 years of
38 age or older does not have to meet the continuing education requirements of this subsection. A
39 licensee who is in active practice as a cosmetologist cosmetologist, hair designer, esthetician,
40 natural hair care specialist, or manicurist and has at least 20 consecutive years of experience as a
41 cosmetologist, in that profession, does not have to meet the continuing education requirements
42 of this subsection, but shall report any continuing education classes completed to the Board,
43 whether the continuing education classes are Board-approved or not. Promotion of products and
44 systems shall be allowed at continuing education given in-house or at trade shows. Continuing
45 education classes may also be offered in secondary languages as needed. No member of the Board
46 may offer continuing education courses as required by this section.
47 (f) If an apprentice, a cosmetologist, hair designer, esthetician, manicurist, natural hair
48 care specialist, or teacher fails to renew his or her license or certification within five years
49 following the expiration date, the licensee shall be required to pass an examination as prescribed
50 by the Board before the license will be reinstated.
Senate Bill 808-Second Edition Page 9

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (g) Cosmetic art school licenses shall be renewed on or before October 1 of each year. A
2 late fee shall be charged for licenses renewed after that date. Any license not renewed by
3 November 1 of that year shall expire. A cosmetic art school whose license has been expired for
4 one year or less shall have its license reinstated upon payment of the reinstatement fee, the late
5 fee, and all unpaid license fees.
6 (h) Upon request by a licensee for inactive status, the Board may place the licensee's
7 name on the inactive list so long as the licensee is in good standing with the Board. An inactive
8 licensee is not required to complete continuing education requirements. An inactive licensee shall
9 not practice cosmetic art for consideration. However, the inactive licensee may continue to
10 purchase supplies as accorded an active licensee. When the inactive licensee desires to be
11 removed from the inactive list and return to active practice, the inactive licensee shall notify the
12 Board of his or her desire to return to active status and pay the required fee as determined by the
13 Board. As a condition of returning to active status, the Board may require the licensee to complete
14 eight to 24 hours of continuing education pursuant to subsection (e) of this section.
15 "§ 88B-22. Licenses and certifications required; criminal penalty.
16 (a) Except as provided in this Chapter, no person may practice or attempt to practice
17 cosmetic art for pay or reward in any form, either directly or indirectly, without being licensed
18 or certified as an apprentice, a cosmetologist, hair designer, esthetician, natural hair care
19 specialist, or manicurist by the Board.
20 (b) Except as provided in this Chapter, no person may practice cosmetic art or any part
21 of cosmetic art, for pay or reward in any form, either directly or indirectly, outside of a licensed
22 cosmetic art shop.shop or mobile cosmetic art shop.
23 (c) No person may open or operate a cosmetic art shop or mobile cosmetic art shop in
24 this State unless a license has been issued by the Board for that shop.shop or mobile cosmetic art
25 shop.
26 (d) An individual certified or licensed as an esthetician, hair designer, natural hair care
27 specialist, or manicurist may practice only that part of cosmetic art for which the individual is
28 certified or licensed.
29 (d1) No person may teach cosmetic art in a Board-approved cosmetic art school unless the
30 person is a teacher licensed under this Chapter. A guest lecturer may be exempt from the
31 requirements of this subsection upon approval by the Board.
32 (e) An apprentice licensed under the provisions of this Chapter shall apprentice under the
33 direct supervision of a cosmetologist. An apprentice shall not operate a cosmetic art shop.
34 (f) A violation of this Chapter is a Class 3 misdemeanor.
35 "§ 88B-23. Licenses and certifications to be posted.
36 (a) Every apprentice, cosmetologist, hair designer, esthetician, manicurist, natural hair
37 care specialist, and teacher licensed under this Chapter shall display the certificate of license
38 issued by the Board within the shop in which the person works.
39 (b) Every certificate of license to operate a cosmetic art shop or shop, mobile cosmetic
40 art shop, or cosmetic art school shall be conspicuously posted in the shop or school for which it
41 is issued.
42 (c) Every natural hair care specialist shall conspicuously display the infection control
43 certification issued by the Board at any place where the natural hair care specialist is practicing
44 natural hair care.
45 "§ 88B-24. Revocation of licenses and other disciplinary measures.
46 The Board may restrict, suspend, revoke, or refuse to issue, renew, or reinstate any license
47 for any of the following:
48 (1) Conviction of a felony shown by certified copy of the record of the court of
49 conviction.
50 (2) Gross malpractice or gross incompetency as determined by the Board.
51 (3) Advertising by means of knowingly false or deceptive statements.
